Exploratory Data Analysis of Kickstarter Data

Description

I found this dataset on kaggle.com and thought it would be interesting to use for Udacity’s Exploratory Data Analysis project.

The set contains the first 4000 Kickstarter projects that were available on Oct. 29, 2016.

Univariate Plots Section

##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
##     0.00     1.00    18.00    97.16    74.00 28000.00

I first want to look at how many of our 4,000 projects have met or exceeded their funding goals so I plotted a histogram of our percentage funded variable, a variable that explains what percentage the project is funded in relation to its fundraising goals (ex: If I need $100 to print a cool sticker design and users have pledged $50, I am 50% funded)

As we can see, the mode occurs somewhere in our 0-5% bucket and the median funded project is 18%. The average is much higher because we have extremely skewed data due to some projects vastly exceeding 100% funding.

Of these 4,000 live projects, how long will they be available on Kickstarter? TO answer this, I took a look at the end.time variable which has the date the project will be removed from Kickstarter. It looks like at this given time, projects end within the next month (this data was pulled on Oct. 29th). I wonder if the approaching holiday season had any influence here…

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##       0     100    1036   10230    5450 1828000

I was wondering how much funding these projects typically get so I plotted a histogram of amounts pledged, the total amount of funding the project has at a given time. It looks like if you only need $1,000 to get your idea started, Kickstarter might be an appropriate platform.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##       0     100    1036   10230    5450 1828000

Since the skew was so extreme on the last plot (I limited our x axis quite a bit) I thought I would adjust the axis by log10 to get a better look at our distribution.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.00   22.00   36.00   35.94   50.00   60.00

I wanted to see how long the average title was, is brevity key or do you want to use all space allotted to hook ‘investors’? It looks like users typically use around 20 or 50 characters as our distribution is somewhat bimodal.

While users may not use their entire title field, they are certainly taking advantage of the blurb! As we can see here, short blurbs are not very common.

The distibution of locations was strongly in favor of the ‘Town’ value, again I had to use logarithmic scaling to represent the huge range of values.

We have a lot of currency option but it looks like Kickstarter is mostly popular with Australia, US, CA, UK, and the EU. In the future, we will only want to use these currencies.

It looks like our currency distributions match up with our items by country. Not much Kickstarter usage in Asian countries.

X is our index in the dataset amt.pledged is the total amount of funding the project has at that time blurb is a text field that describes the project being funded by is the field containing the username of the user asking for funding country is the user’s country currency is the user’s native currency end.time is the date the project will be closed for additional funding location is string field for the users city, town, state, or really any location text percentage.funded is the percentage describing amt pledged / amt needed state is the state or province the user is located in title is the name of the project being funded type is the location type with discrete values, town, island, county, etc url is the link to the project on Kickstarter.com title.length is a feature I engineered that has the length of the title in terms of character count. blurb.length is another engineering feature that has the length of the blurb in terms of character count. weeks.until.end is my final engineered feature that is the number of weeks until the project’s funding period has ended. A value of 0 indicates this current week.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Amount pledged and Percent funded.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I would like to see if there is any relationship between currency (as a substitue for location), endtime, and our amount pledged and percent funded variables.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created title and blurb length columns as well as a weeks until end date column.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

  • Distribution of Percentage Funded showed right skew
  • I used a log10 scale when plotting Amount Pledged as there was very strong right skew
  • Distribution of Title length is roughly bimodal with a mode at the title character limit, 60.
  • Similar to title length, blurb length’s mode appears to be at the character limit ~137. This plot has left skewness.
  • Location type was predominately Town, currency was overwhelmingly USD, and item country was also mostly US. All of these plots’ y-axis have been adjust by log10.

Bivariate Plots Section

I wanted to visualize our text based columns relationship here, we already saw that users are typically using the whole blurb field but not always the full title space, here we can see that by the density of points at the top of the chart.

In the next few plots you will see me plot our text fields (blurb, title) character lengths against our features of interest (amount pledged, percentage pledged). I was really hoping to see more of a relationship between the variables I created and our features of interest but there does not appear to be much there.

Here we are looking at our 2 features of interest plotted against eachother. It looks like most our projects under 50% funding receive less than $5,000, but several projects need less than $5,000 to even meet their funding goals so we some density following the y-axis up.

In the plot above I wanted to see the trend between percentage funded and end time. As we can see, projects with later end time have lower percentages of funding as they likely have not been on Kickstarter as long as those with early November end times.

Here is that same distribution cut by week. In Week 1, it looks like we get a surge of projects funded under 50%. I suspect these are likely joke products or quick fundraisers as there aren’t nearly as many under funded projects in the previous week.

It looks like most projects are receiving fewer than $5,000 in each of the Kickstarter markets, with the US being the largest.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

There is only one weak correlation in all of our data and that is between Amount Pledged and Percentage Funded. Of course we would expect that the more money pledged to your goal, the closer you are to reaching your funding goals.

Title and blurb length, the variables I created, did not prove to have much influence on funding/percentage funded.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Not particularly, I was hoping to find something that might serve as a good predictor for reaching a value of 100 (or greater) in percentage funded, but I do not seem to have any yet.

I may have to revisit this and look for key words in titles and blurbs that might have an association with higher percentage funded scores.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

As you would expect it was a weak correlation between Amount Pledged and Percentage Funded.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
##     0.00     1.00    18.00    97.16    74.00 28000.00

Description One

Above is the distribution of our projects’ percentage funded. Now, these are all ‘live’ projects meaning they are still open for contributions, but as we can see in the end time distribution plot, most of these projects will end in the 4 weeks.

So, with that being said, we can infer that the median percentage funded for a project on Kickstarter with a month left until end time, is 18% funded.

Plot Two

Description Two

In this plot I decided I would try to show percentage funded by the number of weeks left until the end time. We can clearly see that as weeks until end decreased, we saw a larger amount of our data shift to the right, indicating higher percentage of funding.

What I can’t explain is why with 0 weeks left, we have a sudden surge of projects that are funded below the 50% mark (whereas most projects with 1 week left are already past the 50% mark). My guess is the user who created the posting was confused or posted the item as a joke and chose an endtime < 7 days out.

Plot Three

Description Three

For plot 3 I wanted to visualize project funding in relation to how soon the project ends.

I decided to use both percentage funded and amount pledged as variables describing a well funded project and weeks.until.end as our measure for how soon the projects are ending.

Since there is little correlation between any of our variables, this plot may be slightly confusing, but the point I am trying to convey is quite simple; the less time a project has until it ends, the closer the project will be to meeting or exceeding its funding goals. The same rule applies to the amount pledged.

To reiterate, answer the following question: when would you expect a project to be more well funded; the day it is posted on Kickstarter or 3 weeks after it has been posted?

The answer is almost in all cases 3 weeks after. The longer the project is available, the more likely you are to receive pledges from the greater Kickstarter audience.

This is depicted in our visualization by any increase in the x or y axis. As you increase along or axis you will notice gradual color change from yellow to blue.

This is showing that as you look at points with more funding, or closer to their funding goals, you typically find that they have fewer weeks left on Kickstarter.

It looks like projects under the 75% funding level are more likely to have 4 or more weeks remaining until the project ends, while projects that exceed this percentage funding level are often ending in fewer than 2 weeks.

Reflection

Overall this was a fun project, I feel like I have some insight in the world of Kickstarter now.

Successes and Failures

Successes, I was able to get a sense on * the nationality of the Kickstarter userbase * how long projects typically last * % of projects that meet their funding goals * Amounts pledged to a project

Failures, I was not able to * Determine the types of products on kickstarter * Find any strong correlation between our variables and meeting funding goals * Find differences in user usage of Kickstarter by currency

What we learned

  • Kickstarter is a good source for funding if you need less than $4000
  • Most listings take full advantage of title and blurb space
  • Kickstarter is mostly popular in the US
  • Median Percentage funded of items with less than 1 week until end time is 49%

How we can improve

Something I left out of our exploration was that I sorted our percentage funded column descending and took a look at some of the most ‘successful’ products by this measure; most of these were either games or books of some variety.

I would like to be able to create a classifier that could examine the text contents in a title or blurb and determine the ‘item type’. Possible item types from my quick glance would be ‘book’, ‘board game’, ‘card game’, ‘fashion accessory’, ‘technology product’, etc.
